{"title_page": "Victoria Chan-Palay", "text_new": "'''Victoria Lye-Hua Chan-Palay''' (born 9 October 1945) is a [[Singapore]]an-born [[neuroscience|neuroscientist]] who has worked in the [[United States]] and [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"Esquire\">{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/search?tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=As+an+adolescent+in+Singapore,+Chan-Palay+was+a+gifted+science+student|title=Neurobiologist Victoria Chan-Palay|work=Esquire|volume=102|page=36|year=1984|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/about-smith/notable-alumnae/she-went-smith|title=Notable Alumnae: She Went to Smith|publisher=Smith College|accessdate=2012-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027122444/http://www.smith.edu/about-smith/notable-alumnae/she-went-smith|archive-date=2012-10-27|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"SilverTsunami\">{{cite web|url=http://www.silvertsunami.asia/Content/Page.aspx?cp=711|title=Introducing Our Medical Panel|publisher=Silver Tsunami Asia|accessdate=2012-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005011201/http://www.silvertsunami.asia/Content/Page.aspx?cp=711|archive-date=2011-10-05|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChan is the second daughter of noted Singaporean swimming coach Dr. [[Chan Ah Kow]].<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19750615\">{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19750615-1.2.6.aspx|first=Ranee|last=Govindram|title=Ex-swim star gets rare varsity honour; Harvard award for Dr. Chan's daughter Vicky|work=The Straits Times|date=1975-06-15|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\">{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790727.2.68.aspx|first=Dana|last=Lam|title=Singaporean named as US defence chief's assistant|work=The Straits Times|date=1979-07-27|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref> Among her four brothers and two sisters is [[Patricia Chan]], who represented Singapore in swimming at the [[Southeast Asian Games]] in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/><ref>{{cite book|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1376_2010-04-29.html|first=Bonny|last=Tan|chapter=Patricia Chan|title=Singapore Infopedia|date=2010-04-29|accessdate=2012-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219105610/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1376_2010-04-29.html|archive-date=2013-12-19|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> As a young woman, Chan excelled at school in science, and herself represented Singapore in international swimming competitions as well.<ref group=\"Note\">''Esquire'' and Smith College state that she represented [[Singapore at the 1960 Summer Olympics]] in swimming. However, she does not appear in lists of competitors.</ref> She left Singapore in 1962 with a scholarship to [[Smith College]], from which she graduated in 1965.<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/><ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/> She then went on to the [[Tufts University School of Medicine]] for a Ph.D., which she completed in 1969.<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/> While living in the [[Greater Boston]] area, she met [[Sanford Palay]], and married him in 1970.<ref name=\"NYT20020902\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/02/us/sanford-l-palay-83-innovator-in-neuroscience.html|first=Anahad|last=O'Connor|title=Sanford L. Palay, 83, Innovator in Neuroscience|work=The New York Times|date=2002-09-02|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref> She graduated from [[Harvard Medical School]] in 1975 as the first woman to receive an M.D. summa cum laude.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19750615\"/><ref name=\"Smith2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/newsoffice/releases/remarkable.html|title=Julia Child, Betty Friedan and Other Remarkable Alumnae to Be Honored at Smith Celebration|publisher=Smith College|date=1999-10-11|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref>\n\nChan-Palay had two daughters Vicky and Rebecca, the latter with her husband Sanford Palay.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/> However, their marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=\"NYT20020902\"/>\n\n==Scientific career==\nChan-Palay did seminal research in neuroscience with her husband in the 1970s.<ref name=\"NYT20020902\"/> She would go on to found the journal ''Dementia and Geriatric Cognitive Disorders''.<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/> She was named a [[White House Fellows|White House Fellow]] and an assistant to Secretary of Defense [[Harold Brown (Secretary of Defense)|Harold Brown]] in 1979, making her one of the first Singaporeans to achieve such a high rank in the United States government.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/> She later moved to Switzerland, where she served as part of the faculty of [[University of Zurich]] Medical School from 1989. She was awarded the [[Humboldt Prize]] in Medical Research by the [[Alexander von Humboldt Foundation]].<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/> She [[relinquishment of United States nationality|relinquished United States citizenship]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2012/11/01/2012-26841/quarterly-publication-of-individuals-who-have-chosen-to-expatriate-as-required-by-section-6039g|first=Ann|last=Gaudelli|title=Quarterly Publication of Individuals, Who Have Chosen to Expatriate, As Required by Section 6039G|work=Federal Register|volume=77|page=66084|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book|first=Victoria Lye-Hua|last=Chan-Curtis|title=Cytochemical localization of the nucleic acids by an acriflavine-phosphotungstate complex for fluorescence microscopy and electron microscopy|series=Ph.D. Dissertation|publisher=Tufts University|date=October 1969|oclc=11410563}}\n*{{cite book|first=Sanford L.|last=Palay|first2=Victoria|last2=Chan-Palay|title=Cerebellar cortex: cytology and organization|publisher=Springer|year=1974|oclc=1367086}}\n*{{cite book|first=Victoria|last=Chan-Palay|title=Cerebellar dentate nucleus: organization, cytology and transmitters|publisher=Springer-Verlag|year=1977|oclc=2542632}}\n*{{cite book|first=Victoria|last=Chan-Palay|first2=Sanford L.|last2=Palay|title=Cytochemical methods in neuroanatomy|url=https://archive.org/details/cytochemicalmeth0000chan|url-access=registration|publisher=A. R. Liss|year=1982|oclc=8451650}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chan-Palay, Victoria}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean sportswomen]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People who lost United States citizenship]]\n[[Category:Harvard Medical School alumni]]\n[[Category:Smith College alumni]]\n[[Category:Tufts University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Zurich faculty]]\n[[Category:Swiss neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Swiss women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Singaporean descent]]\n[[Category:Singaporean expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:White House Fellows]]\n", "text_old": "'''Victoria Lye-Hua Chan-Palay''' (born 9 October 1945) is a [[Singapore]]an-born [[neuroscience|neuroscientist]] who has worked in the [[United States]] and [[Switzerland]].<ref name=\"Esquire\">{{cite news|url=https://www.google.com/search?tbo=p&tbm=bks&q=As+an+adolescent+in+Singapore,+Chan-Palay+was+a+gifted+science+student|title=Neurobiologist Victoria Chan-Palay|work=Esquire|volume=102|page=36|year=1984|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref name=\"Smith\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/about-smith/notable-alumnae/she-went-smith|title=Notable Alumnae: She Went to Smith|publisher=Smith College|accessdate=2012-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121027122444/http://www.smith.edu/about-smith/notable-alumnae/she-went-smith|archive-date=2012-10-27|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref><ref name=\"SilverTsunami\">{{cite web|url=http://www.silvertsunami.asia/Content/Page.aspx?cp=711|title=Introducing Our Medical Advisory Panal|publisher=Silver Tsunami Asia|accessdate=2012-11-01|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111005011201/http://www.silvertsunami.asia/Content/Page.aspx?cp=711|archive-date=2011-10-05|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nChan is the second daughter of noted Singaporean swimming coach Dr. [[Chan Ah Kow]].<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19750615\">{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19750615-1.2.6.aspx|first=Ranee|last=Govindram|title=Ex-swim star gets rare varsity honour; Harvard award for Dr. Chan's daughter Vicky|work=The Straits Times|date=1975-06-15|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref><ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\">{{cite news|url=http://newspapers.nl.sg/Digitised/Article/straitstimes19790727.2.68.aspx|first=Dana|last=Lam|title=Singaporean named as US defence chief's assistant|work=The Straits Times|date=1979-07-27|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref> Among her four brothers and two sisters is [[Patricia Chan]], who represented Singapore in swimming at the [[Southeast Asian Games]] in the 1960s and 1970s.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/><ref>{{cite book|url=http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1376_2010-04-29.html|first=Bonny|last=Tan|chapter=Patricia Chan|title=Singapore Infopedia|date=2010-04-29|accessdate=2012-11-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131219105610/http://infopedia.nl.sg/articles/SIP_1376_2010-04-29.html|archive-date=2013-12-19|url-status=dead|df=}}</ref> As a young woman, Chan excelled at school in science, and herself represented Singapore in international swimming competitions as well.<ref group=\"Note\">''Esquire'' and Smith College state that she represented [[Singapore at the 1960 Summer Olympics]] in swimming. However, she does not appear in lists of competitors.</ref> She left Singapore in 1962 with a scholarship to [[Smith College]], from which she graduated in 1965.<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/><ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/> She then went on to the [[Tufts University School of Medicine]] for a Ph.D., which she completed in 1969.<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/> While living in the [[Greater Boston]] area, she met [[Sanford Palay]], and married him in 1970.<ref name=\"NYT20020902\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/02/us/sanford-l-palay-83-innovator-in-neuroscience.html|first=Anahad|last=O'Connor|title=Sanford L. Palay, 83, Innovator in Neuroscience|work=The New York Times|date=2002-09-02|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref> She graduated from [[Harvard Medical School]] in 1975 as the first woman to receive an M.D. summa cum laude.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19750615\"/><ref name=\"Smith2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.smith.edu/newsoffice/releases/remarkable.html|title=Julia Child, Betty Friedan and Other Remarkable Alumnae to Be Honored at Smith Celebration|publisher=Smith College|date=1999-10-11|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref>\n\nChan-Palay had two daughters Vicky and Rebecca, the latter with her husband Sanford Palay.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/> However, their marriage ended in divorce.<ref name=\"NYT20020902\"/>\n\n==Scientific career==\nChan-Palay did seminal research in neuroscience with her husband in the 1970s.<ref name=\"NYT20020902\"/> She would go on to found the journal ''Dementia and Geriatric Cognitive Disorders''.<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/> She was named a [[White House Fellows|White House Fellow]] and an assistant to Secretary of Defense [[Harold Brown (Secretary of Defense)|Harold Brown]] in 1979, making her one of the first Singaporeans to achieve such a high rank in the United States government.<ref name=\"StraitsTimes19790727\"/> She later moved to Switzerland, where she served as part of the faculty of [[University of Zurich]] Medical School from 1989. She was awarded the [[Humboldt Prize]] in Medical Research by the [[Alexander von Humboldt Foundation]].<ref name=\"SilverTsunami\"/> She [[relinquishment of United States nationality|relinquished United States citizenship]] in 2012.<ref>{{cite journal|url=https://www.federalregister.gov/articles/2012/11/01/2012-26841/quarterly-publication-of-individuals-who-have-chosen-to-expatriate-as-required-by-section-6039g|first=Ann|last=Gaudelli|title=Quarterly Publication of Individuals, Who Have Chosen to Expatriate, As Required by Section 6039G|work=Federal Register|volume=77|page=66084|accessdate=2012-11-01}}</ref>\n\n==Works==\n*{{cite book|first=Victoria Lye-Hua|last=Chan-Curtis|title=Cytochemical localization of the nucleic acids by an acriflavine-phosphotungstate complex for fluorescence microscopy and electron microscopy|series=Ph.D. Dissertation|publisher=Tufts University|date=October 1969|oclc=11410563}}\n*{{cite book|first=Sanford L.|last=Palay|first2=Victoria|last2=Chan-Palay|title=Cerebellar cortex: cytology and organization|publisher=Springer|year=1974|oclc=1367086}}\n*{{cite book|first=Victoria|last=Chan-Palay|title=Cerebellar dentate nucleus: organization, cytology and transmitters|publisher=Springer-Verlag|year=1977|oclc=2542632}}\n*{{cite book|first=Victoria|last=Chan-Palay|first2=Sanford L.|last2=Palay|title=Cytochemical methods in neuroanatomy|url=https://archive.org/details/cytochemicalmeth0000chan|url-access=registration|publisher=A. R. Liss|year=1982|oclc=8451650}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=Note}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chan-Palay, Victoria}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Singaporean sportswomen]]\n[[Category:Singaporean emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:People who lost United States citizenship]]\n[[Category:Harvard Medical School alumni]]\n[[Category:Smith College alumni]]\n[[Category:Tufts University School of Medicine alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Zurich faculty]]\n[[Category:Swiss neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Swiss women neuroscientists]]\n[[Category:Swiss people of Singaporean descent]]\n[[Category:Singaporean expatriates in Switzerland]]\n[[Category:White House Fellows]]\n", "name_user": "John of Reading", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Updated a cited \"title\" based on the page at Archive.org", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoria_Chan-Palay"}
{"title_page": "Gregory Salcido", "text_new": "{{notability|date=June 2019}}\n[[File:Gregory Salcido.jpg|thumb|Gregory Salcido]]\n'''Gregory Salcido''' (born July 4, 1968) is a  former [[Pico Rivera]] [[City Council]]man, former candidate for [[United States Congress|Congress]] and former educator in [[Pico Rivera]], California. Concurrently with his position as city councilman, Salcido served as mayor of Pico Rivera in 2002, 2010 and 2015. His derogatory comments about members of the [[United States Military|United States armed forces]], captured on video by one of his students, went viral in January 2018, leading to calls for his eventual dismissal as both teacher and city councilman in March 2018.<ref name=\"Pico Rivera councilman, teacher recorded making anti-military rant in classroom\">{{cite web\n|url = http://abc7.com/education/pico-rivera-councilman-under-fire-for-anti-military-rant-in-classroom/2997385/\n|title = Gregory Salcido\n|publisher = abc7.com\n}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSalcido was born in [[East Los Angeles, California]] in 1968 to first-generation [[Mexican-American]]s. His grandparents emigrated from [[Torre\u00f3n]], [[Coahuila]] in northeast Mexico.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.pico-rivera.org/depts/council/gsalcido.asp\n|title = Gregory Salcido City Council Page\n|publisher = City of Pico Rivera\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Mayoral duty No. 1: Teach history\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.csmonitor.com/2002/0430/p14s01-lecl.html\n|title = Mayoral duty No. 1: Teach history\n|publisher = Christian Science Monitor\n}}</ref> His father was a steelworker.<ref name=\"Mayoral duty No. 1: Teach history\"/> Salcido graduated from [[El Rancho High School]], where he would later become a teacher, in 1986.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/> Salcido received his bachelor's degree in history from [[Whittier College]].<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/> Salcido started teaching in 1998 a few months after graduating from college.<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2010/07/21/parents-complaints-send-mayor-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-salcido-on-administrative-leave/\n|title = Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\n|publisher = Whittier Daily News\n}}</ref> A year later, Salcido ran for and won a position on the Pico Rivera City Council. Much of his philosophy and views on life come from watching stand up comedy. One of his all time favorites was [[George Carlin]]. He mimicked his anti authoritarian values using many of his jokes to inspire and flip peoples views on life.\n\n==Career and controversies as educator==\nSalcido began his teaching career at his alma mater, [[El Rancho High School]], in 1998.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/> His tenure as teacher at El Rancho was marred by controversy. On three separate occasions, Salcido has been put on administrative leave.\n\nIn 2005, a parent complained about a class discussion about masturbation. Investigators with the Los Angeles Sheriff's Department cleared Salcido of any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"Anti-military rant\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.dailybreeze.com/2018/01/29/anti-military-rant-not-first-time-pico-rivera-councilman-teacher-gregory-salcido-has-been-in-trouble-for-in-class-behavior/\n|title = Anti-military rant not first time Pico Rivera councilman, teacher Gregory Salcido has been in trouble for in-class behavior\n|publisher = Daily Breeze\n}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Salcido was reprimanded and placed on administrative leave after a parent complained about Salcido's conduct in the classroom.<ref name=\"Salcido repimanded but will return\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.sbsun.com/2010/07/23/salcido-repimanded-but-will-return-to-teach-in-the-fall/\n|title = Salcido repimanded but will return to teach in the fall\n|publisher = Santa Barbara Sun\n}}</ref> A parent alleged that his Anglo-American 16-year-old daughter had been threatened by Salcido and that Salcido had made inappropriate insulting comments about race, other students and parents.<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\"/> One student complained that Salcido had said, \"Shut up, Kelly, before I kill you.\"<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\"/><ref name=\"Salcido repimanded but will return\"/>\n\nIn May 2012, Salcido was placed on administrative leave after the [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] received a complaint that he had struck an Anglo-American student. Salcido admitted striking the student and said the student had been disruptive by sleeping in class.<ref name=\"El Rancho High teacher placed on leave after admittedly \u2018smacking\u2019 a student\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.dailynews.com/2012/05/16/el-rancho-high-teacher-placed-on-leave-after-admittedly-smacking-a-student/\n|title = El Rancho High teacher placed on leave after admittedly \u2018smacking\u2019 a student\n|publisher = Los Angeles Daily News\n}}</ref> The child, named David, also alleged that Salcido bullied him in a sexually derisive and dismissive manner based on the boy's weight and appearance, calling him \"[[Chaz Bono]]\".<ref name=\"Pico Rivera high school teacher, council member admits to smacking unmotivated student\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.scpr.org/blogs/news/2012/05/17/6166/pico-rivera-high-school-teacher-council-member-adm/\n|title = Pico Rivera high school teacher, council member admits to smacking unmotivated student\n|publisher = 89.9 KPCC\n}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, a student recorded a video in his classroom of Salcido lecturing about the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. military]] after Salcido noticed a student wearing a [[United States Marines|Marine Corps]] shirt. Salcido's disparaging remarks about U.S. servicemen attracted widespread local, statewide and nationwide media attention. The video, which was laced with profanity, caused a nationwide furor, with people across the country calling for Salcido's termination by the [[El Rancho Unified School District]] and removal from the Pico Rivera City Council. In the video, Salcido said, \"We\u2019ve got a bunch of dumbshits over there. Think about the people who you know who are over there, your freaking stupid uncle Louis or whatever; they\u2019re dumbshits. They\u2019re not like high-level thinkers, they\u2019re not academic people, they\u2019re not intellectual people, they\u2019re the freaking lowest of our low. Not morally, I\u2019m not saying they make bad moral decisions, they\u2019re not talented people.\"<ref name=\"Teacher Gregory Salcido Says Military Are \u2018Dumbsh*ts\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.educationviews.org/teacher-gregory-salcido-says-military-are-dumbshts/\n|title = Teacher Gregory Salcido Says Military Are \u2018Dumbsh*ts\n|publisher = Education Views\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2018/01/27/pico-rivera-councilman-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-gregory-salcido-caught-on-tape-degrading-military/|title=Pico Rivera councilman and El Rancho High teacher Gregory Salcido caught on video degrading military|date=2018-01-27|work=Whittier Daily News|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}\n</ref><ref name=\"whittierdailynews.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2010/07/21/parents-complaints-send-mayor-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-salcido-on-administrative-leave|title=Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave|date=2010-07-21|work=Whittier Daily News|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn the video, Salcido questioned the military's ability to succeed in its ongoing operations in the Middle East, saying, \"We all have night-vision goggles, all that kind of stuff, and we can\u2019t freakin\u2019 control these dudes wearing freakin\u2019 robes and chanclas [flip-flops] because we have a bunch of dumbshits over there.\" Salcido also referred to military actions during the Vietnam War as fighting a \"bunch of people this freakin\u2019 big throwing rice at us.\u201d  He questioned why the school would allow the military to recruit students, saying, \"I don\u2019t understand why we let the freakin\u2019 military guys come over here and recruit you at school. We don\u2019t have pimps come into school. Anyone interested in being a hoe [whore]?\"<ref name=\"Pentagon responds to California teacher who was recorded calling US troops 'a bunch of dumb s--ts'\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/pentagon-responds-to-california-teacher-who-was-recorded-calling-us-troops-a-bunch-of-dumb-s-ts/article/2647423/\n|title = Pentagon responds to California teacher who was recorded calling US troops 'a bunch of dumb s--ts'\n|publisher = Washington Examiner\n}}</ref> According to the student who made the video, Salcido has a history of making anti-military statements.<ref name=\"Students gives his side of story\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2018/01/29/student-who-triggered-military-hating-california-teacher-gives-his-side-story.html\n|title = Student who triggered military-hating California teacher gives his side of the story\n|publisher = Fox News\n}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of his videotaped comments, Salcido was placed on administrative leave pending the results of an investigation.<ref name=\"whittierdailynews.com\"/>\n\nOn March 21st, 2018 School Board President Aurora Villon announced that the El Rancho Unified School District had voted unanimously on March 20 to terminate Gregory Salcido from his teaching position.<ref>https://www.themaven.net/bluelivesmatter/news/city-council-eliminates-teacher-who-called-military-lowest-of-our-low-kuBrqRpIvkaHnKXMZDyOBg?full=1</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, the El Rancho Unified School District released an official report on Salcido's tenure in the school district and found an ongoing history of questionable and abusive behavior towards students who were pro-military, [[Christians|Christian]], [[LGBT]], Anglo-American, and Asian-American. One counselor told investigators that they had to move over 25 students from Salcido's classes over the years for the students' well-being, due to berating behavior from Salcido. In addition to his behavior towards students, Salcido also used his district-owned computer to save nude images of women; a violation of the district's technology use policies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-edu-greg-salcido-investigation-20180418-story.html|title=Fired Pico Rivera teacher bullied students, saved pictures of nude women on class computer, report says|last=Kohli|first=Sonali|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nSalcido has served on the [[Pico Rivera]] [[City Council]] since 2000. During his tenure, Salcido has been at odds with the council on several key issues.<ref name=\"El Rancho High School teacher Gregory Salcido put on administrative leave following anti-military tirade\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2018/01/29/el-rancho-high-school-teacher-put-on-administrative-leave-following-anti-military-tirade/\n|title = El Rancho High School teacher Gregory Salcido put on administrative leave following anti-military tirade\n|publisher = Whittier Daily News\n}}</ref> Generally regarded as a [[Progressivism|progressive]] [[Democratic Party|Democrat]], Salcido has taken positions on the [[left wing]] of the [[Democratic Party]], such as his decision in January 2010 to remove the [[Bible]] from the City Council dais for violating the Constitution's Establishment Clause.<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints\">{{cite web\n|url =https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2010/07/21/parents-complaints-send-mayor-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-salcido-on-administrative-leave/\n|title = Parent\u2019s complaints\n|publisher = Pasadena Star News\n}}</ref> In 2002, while serving as mayor of Pico Rivera, Salcido ran for [[California's 38th congressional district]] and raised $62,000, but lost in the Democratic primary to [[Grace Napolitano]].<ref name=\"Anti-military rant\"/><ref name=\"GREGORY SALCIDO FOR CONGRESS\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.fec.gov/data/committee/C00370478/?tab=summary\n|title = GREGORY SALCIDO FOR CONGRESS\n|publisher = Federal Election Commission\n}}</ref> Salcido has served as a member of the History and Heritage Society Committee and has represented the city in various countywide organizations, such as the Los Angeles County City Selection Committee and the Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/>\n\nIn 2004, a committee was organized to recall Salcido and two other council members after the three approved a $40,000 raise for the then city manager, but the recall effort failed.<ref name=\"Pico Rivera ousts planning commissioner\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.dailynews.com/2005/10/19/pico-rivera-ousts-planning-commissioner/\n|title = Pico Rivera ousts planning commissioner \n|publisher = Los Angeles Daily News\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Salcido was fined by the [[California Fair Political Practices Commission]] for campaign finance violations and fined $2,500.<ref name=\"In the Matter of: GREGORY SALCIDO and GREGORY SALCIDO \u2013 CITY COUNCIL \">{{cite web\n|url =http://www.fppc.ca.gov/content/dam/fppc/documents/Stipulations/2012/December/16salcido%20stip%20and%20exh.pdf\n|title = In the Matter of: GREGORY SALCIDO and GREGORY SALCIDO \u2013 CITY COUNCIL \n|publisher = California Fair Political Practices Commission\n}}</ref><ref name=\"El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.loscerritosnews.net/2015/02/25/el-rodeo-nightclub-in-pico-rivera-raided-by-the-dea-and-fbi/\n|title = El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI \n|publisher = Cerritos  Community News\n}}</ref> This fine was in connection to a cash donation by the El Rodeo Nightclub of $2,000, which is more than the California limit of $100 on cash donations. The nightclub had been raided by the [[Drug Enforcement Agency]] and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] due to suspected drug money laundering.<ref name=\"El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI\"/> The nightclub had been a source of complaints by residents and other city council members, but Salcido never took any action as councilman on those complaints.<ref name=\"El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI\"/>\n\n==Aftermath of video controversy==\nOn January 29, 2018 the City Council censured Salcido for his comments after his videotaped anti-military tirade, although there are questions about whether the First Amendment allows a city government to take action for unpopular speech.<ref name=\"Teacher Removed From City Council\">{{cite web\n|url = http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2018/01/29/teacher-anti-military-mayor-city-council/\n|title = Teacher Removed From City Council \n|publisher = CBS Los Angeles\n}}</ref> The City Council released a statement unanimously condemning Salcido's remarks.<ref name=\"Teacher Removed From City Council\"/> Salcido is forbidden from chairing or participating in any committees.\n\nA Pico Rivera eatery, Zapien's Salsa Grill, removed a popular lunch special named after Salcido after the  video surfaced. The lunch special, called \"The Mayor,\" was a common dish consisting of two enchiladas frequently ordered by Salcido, a regular at the restaurant. In a statement, the restaurant's proprietor said, \"I am outraged by what he said against our military personnel and our veterans.\"<ref name=\"Pico Rivera eatery takes \u2018The Mayor,\u2019 off the menu\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.presstelegram.com/2018/01/29/amid-controversy-pico-rivera-eatery-takes-the-mayor-named-after-gregory-salcido-off-the-menu/\n|title = Pico Rivera eatery takes \u2018The Mayor,\u2019 off the menu \n|publisher = Press Telegram\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Zapien's Salsa Grill Lunch Specials\">{{cite web\n|url = http://thesalsagrill.com/menu/lunch-specials\n|title = Lunch Specials\n|publisher = Zapien's Salsa Grill\n}}</ref>\n\nOn Friday, February 1st, classes at El Rancho were cancelled as a protest took place across the street from the school. The event was covered by local media sources.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2018/02/01/classes-canceled-for-el-rancho-high-students-friday-same-day-as-gregory-salcido-protest-planned/|title=Classes canceled for El Rancho High students Friday, same day as Gregory Salcido protest planned|date=2018-02-02|work=Whittier Daily News|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSalcido was finally fired by the El Rancho Unified School District on March 20, 2018. The event caused explosive cheering when the results of an investigation was announced to the general public at a school board meeting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/03/21/teacher-who-called-military-lowest-low-is-fired.html\n|title=Teacher who called military 'lowest of the low' is fired|work=Fox News}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salcido, Gregory}}\n[[Category:Mayors of places in California]]\n[[Category:People from Pico Rivera, California]]\n[[Category:Whittier College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California city council members]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:People from East Los Angeles, California]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2002 United States elections]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{notability|date=June 2019}}\n[[File:Gregory Salcido.jpg|thumb|Gregory Salcido]]\n'''Gregory Salcido''' (born July 4, 1968) is a  former [[Pico Rivera]] [[City Council]]man, former candidate for [[United States Congress|Congress]] and former educator in [[Pico Rivera]], California. Concurrently with his position as city councilman, Salcido served as mayor of Pico Rivera in 2002, 2010 and 2015. His derogatory comments about members of the [[United States Military|United States armed forces]], captured on video by one of his students, went viral in January 2018, leading to calls for his eventual dismissal as both teacher and city councilman in March 2018.<ref name=\"Pico Rivera councilman, teacher recorded making anti-military rant in classroom\">{{cite web\n|url = http://abc7.com/education/pico-rivera-councilman-under-fire-for-anti-military-rant-in-classroom/2997385/\n|title = Gregory Salcido\n|publisher = abc7.com\n}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nSalcido was born in [[East Los Angeles, California]] in 1968 to first-generation [[Mexican-American]]s. His grandparents emigrated from [[Torre\u00f3n]], [[Coahuila]] in northeast Mexico.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.pico-rivera.org/depts/council/gsalcido.asp\n|title = Gregory Salcido City Council Page\n|publisher = City of Pico Rivera\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Mayoral duty No. 1: Teach history\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.csmonitor.com/2002/0430/p14s01-lecl.html\n|title = Mayoral duty No. 1: Teach history\n|publisher = Christian Science Monitor\n}}</ref> His father was a steelworker.<ref name=\"Mayoral duty No. 1: Teach history\"/> Salcido graduated from [[El Rancho High School]], where he would later become a teacher, in 1986.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/> Salcido received his bachelor's degree in history from [[Whittier College]].<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/> Salcido started teaching in 1998 a few months after graduating from college.<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2010/07/21/parents-complaints-send-mayor-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-salcido-on-administrative-leave/\n|title = Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\n|publisher = Whittier Daily News\n}}</ref> A year later, Salcido ran for and won a position on the Pico Rivera City Council. Much of his philosophy and views on life come from watching stand up comedy. One of his all time favorites was [[George Carlin]]. He mimicked his anti authoritarian values using many of his jokes to inspire and flip peoples views on life.\n\n==Career and controversies as educator==\nSalcido began his teaching career at his alma mater, [[El Rancho High School]], in 1998.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/> His tenure as teacher at El Rancho was marred by controversy. On three separate occasions, Salcido has been put on administrative leave.\n\nIn 2005, a parent complained about a class discussion about masturbation. Investigators with the Los Angeles Sheriff's Department cleared Salcido of any wrongdoing.<ref name=\"Anti-military rant\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.dailybreeze.com/2018/01/29/anti-military-rant-not-first-time-pico-rivera-councilman-teacher-gregory-salcido-has-been-in-trouble-for-in-class-behavior/\n|title = Anti-military rant not first time Pico Rivera councilman, teacher Gregory Salcido has been in trouble for in-class behavior\n|publisher = Daily Breeze\n}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2010, Salcido was reprimanded and placed on administrative leave after a parent complained about Salcido's conduct in the classroom.<ref name=\"Salcido repimanded but will return\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.sbsun.com/2010/07/23/salcido-repimanded-but-will-return-to-teach-in-the-fall/\n|title = Salcido repimanded but will return to teach in the fall\n|publisher = Santa Barbara Sun\n}}</ref> A parent alleged that his Anglo-American 16-year-old daughter had been threatened by Salcido and that Salcido had made inappropriate insulting comments about race, other students and parents.<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\"/> One student complained that Salcido had said, \"Shut up, Kelly, before I kill you.\"<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave\"/><ref name=\"Salcido repimanded but will return\"/>\n\nIn May 2012, Salcido was placed on administrative leave after the [[Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department]] received a complaint that he had struck an Anglo-American student. Salcido admitted striking the student and said the student had been disruptive by sleeping in class.<ref name=\"El Rancho High teacher placed on leave after admittedly \u2018smacking\u2019 a student\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.dailynews.com/2012/05/16/el-rancho-high-teacher-placed-on-leave-after-admittedly-smacking-a-student/\n|title = El Rancho High teacher placed on leave after admittedly \u2018smacking\u2019 a student\n|publisher = Los Angeles Daily News\n}}</ref> The child, named David, also alleged that Salcido bullied him in a sexually derisive and dismissive manner based on the boy's weight and appearance, calling him \"[[Chaz Bono]]\".<ref name=\"Pico Rivera high school teacher, council member admits to smacking unmotivated student\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.scpr.org/blogs/news/2012/05/17/6166/pico-rivera-high-school-teacher-council-member-adm/\n|title = Pico Rivera high school teacher, council member admits to smacking unmotivated student\n|publisher = 89.9 KPCC\n}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, a student recorded a video in his classroom of Salcido lecturing about the [[United States Armed Forces|U.S. military]] after Salcido noticed a student wearing a [[United States Marines|Marine Corps]] shirt. Salcido's disparaging remarks about U.S. servicemen attracted widespread local, statewide and nationwide media attention. The video, which was laced with profanity, caused a nationwide furor, with people across the country calling for Salcido's termination by the [[El Rancho Unified School District]] and removal from the Pico Rivera City Council. In the video, Salcido said, \"We\u2019ve got a bunch of dumbshits over there. Think about the people who you know who are over there, your freaking stupid uncle Louis or whatever; they\u2019re dumbshits. They\u2019re not like high-level thinkers, they\u2019re not academic people, they\u2019re not intellectual people, they\u2019re the freaking lowest of our low. Not morally, I\u2019m not saying they make bad moral decisions, they\u2019re not talented people.\"<ref name=\"Teacher Gregory Salcido Says Military Are \u2018Dumbsh*ts\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.educationviews.org/teacher-gregory-salcido-says-military-are-dumbshts/\n|title = Teacher Gregory Salcido Says Military Are \u2018Dumbsh*ts\n|publisher = Education Views\n}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2018/01/27/pico-rivera-councilman-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-gregory-salcido-caught-on-tape-degrading-military/|title=Pico Rivera councilman and El Rancho High teacher Gregory Salcido caught on video degrading military|date=2018-01-27|work=Whittier Daily News|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}\n</ref><ref name=\"whittierdailynews.com\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2010/07/21/parents-complaints-send-mayor-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-salcido-on-administrative-leave|title=Parent\u2019s complaints send mayor and El Rancho High teacher Salcido on administrative leave|date=2010-07-21|work=Whittier Daily News|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIn the video, Salcido questioned the military's ability to succeed in its ongoing operations in the Middle East, saying, \"We all have night-vision goggles, all that kind of stuff, and we can\u2019t freakin\u2019 control these dudes wearing freakin\u2019 robes and chanclas [flip-flops] because we have a bunch of dumbshits over there.\" Salcido also referred to military actions during the Vietnam War as fighting a \"bunch of people this freakin\u2019 big throwing rice at us.\u201d  He questioned why the school would allow the military to recruit students, saying, \"I don\u2019t understand why we let the freakin\u2019 military guys come over here and recruit you at school. We don\u2019t have pimps come into school. Anyone interested in being a hoe [whore]?\"<ref name=\"Pentagon responds to California teacher who was recorded calling US troops 'a bunch of dumb s--ts'\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/pentagon-responds-to-california-teacher-who-was-recorded-calling-us-troops-a-bunch-of-dumb-s-ts/article/2647423/\n|title = Pentagon responds to California teacher who was recorded calling US troops 'a bunch of dumb s--ts'\n|publisher = Washington Examiner\n}}</ref> According to the student who made the video, Salcido has a history of making anti-military statements.<ref name=\"Students gives his side of story\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.foxnews.com/opinion/2018/01/29/student-who-triggered-military-hating-california-teacher-gives-his-side-story.html\n|title = Student who triggered military-hating California teacher gives his side of the story\n|publisher = Fox News\n}}</ref>\n\nAs a result of his videotaped comments, Salcido was placed on administrative leave pending the results of an investigation.<ref name=\"whittierdailynews.com\"/>\n\nOn March 21st, 2018 School Board President Aurora Villon announced that the El Rancho Unified School District had voted unanimously on March 20 to terminate Gregory Salcido from his teaching position.<ref>https://www.themaven.net/bluelivesmatter/news/city-council-eliminates-teacher-who-called-military-lowest-of-our-low-kuBrqRpIvkaHnKXMZDyOBg?full=1</ref>\n\nIn April 2018, the El Rancho Unified School District released an official report on Salcido's tenure in the school district and found an ongoing history of questionable and abusive behavior towards students who were pro-military, [[Christians|Christian]], [[LGBT]], Anglo-American, and Asian-American. One counselor told investigators that they had to move over 25 students from Salcido's classes over the years for the students' well-being, due to berating behavior from Salcido. In addition to his behavior towards students, Salcido also used his district-owned computer to save nude images of women; a violation of the district's technology use policies.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/local/lanow/la-me-edu-greg-salcido-investigation-20180418-story.html|title=Fired Pico Rivera teacher bullied students, saved pictures of nude women on class computer, report says|last=Kohli|first=Sonali|website=latimes.com|access-date=2018-05-28}}</ref>\n\n==Political career==\nSalcido has served on the [[Pico Rivera]] [[City Council]] since 2000. During his tenure, Salcido has been at odds with the council on several key issues.<ref name=\"El Rancho High School teacher Gregory Salcido put on administrative leave following anti-military tirade\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2018/01/29/el-rancho-high-school-teacher-put-on-administrative-leave-following-anti-military-tirade/\n|title = El Rancho High School teacher Gregory Salcido put on administrative leave following anti-military tirade\n|publisher = Whittier Daily News\n}}</ref> Generally regarded as a [[progressive]] [[Democratic Party|Democrat]], Salcido has taken positions on the [[left wing]] of the [[Democratic Party]], such as his decision in January 2010 to remove the [[Bible]] from the City Council dais for violating the Constitution's Establishment Clause.<ref name=\"Parent\u2019s complaints\">{{cite web\n|url =https://www.pasadenastarnews.com/2010/07/21/parents-complaints-send-mayor-and-el-rancho-high-teacher-salcido-on-administrative-leave/\n|title = Parent\u2019s complaints\n|publisher = Pasadena Star News\n}}</ref> In 2002, while serving as mayor of Pico Rivera, Salcido ran for [[California's 38th congressional district]] and raised $62,000, but lost in the Democratic primary to [[Grace Napolitano]].<ref name=\"Anti-military rant\"/><ref name=\"GREGORY SALCIDO FOR CONGRESS\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.fec.gov/data/committee/C00370478/?tab=summary\n|title = GREGORY SALCIDO FOR CONGRESS\n|publisher = Federal Election Commission\n}}</ref> Salcido has served as a member of the History and Heritage Society Committee and has represented the city in various countywide organizations, such as the Los Angeles County City Selection Committee and the Sanitation Districts of Los Angeles County.<ref name=\"Gregory Salcido City Council Page\"/>\n\nIn 2004, a committee was organized to recall Salcido and two other council members after the three approved a $40,000 raise for the then city manager, but the recall effort failed.<ref name=\"Pico Rivera ousts planning commissioner\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.dailynews.com/2005/10/19/pico-rivera-ousts-planning-commissioner/\n|title = Pico Rivera ousts planning commissioner \n|publisher = Los Angeles Daily News\n}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, Salcido was fined by the [[California Fair Political Practices Commission]] for campaign finance violations and fined $2,500.<ref name=\"In the Matter of: GREGORY SALCIDO and GREGORY SALCIDO \u2013 CITY COUNCIL \">{{cite web\n|url =http://www.fppc.ca.gov/content/dam/fppc/documents/Stipulations/2012/December/16salcido%20stip%20and%20exh.pdf\n|title = In the Matter of: GREGORY SALCIDO and GREGORY SALCIDO \u2013 CITY COUNCIL \n|publisher = California Fair Political Practices Commission\n}}</ref><ref name=\"El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI\">{{cite web\n|url = http://www.loscerritosnews.net/2015/02/25/el-rodeo-nightclub-in-pico-rivera-raided-by-the-dea-and-fbi/\n|title = El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI \n|publisher = Cerritos  Community News\n}}</ref> This fine was in connection to a cash donation by the El Rodeo Nightclub of $2,000, which is more than the California limit of $100 on cash donations. The nightclub had been raided by the [[Drug Enforcement Agency]] and [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] due to suspected drug money laundering.<ref name=\"El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI\"/> The nightclub had been a source of complaints by residents and other city council members, but Salcido never took any action as councilman on those complaints.<ref name=\"El Rodeo Nightclub in Pico Rivera Raided by the DEA and FBI\"/>\n\n==Aftermath of video controversy==\nOn January 29, 2018 the City Council censured Salcido for his comments after his videotaped anti-military tirade, although there are questions about whether the First Amendment allows a city government to take action for unpopular speech.<ref name=\"Teacher Removed From City Council\">{{cite web\n|url = http://losangeles.cbslocal.com/2018/01/29/teacher-anti-military-mayor-city-council/\n|title = Teacher Removed From City Council \n|publisher = CBS Los Angeles\n}}</ref> The City Council released a statement unanimously condemning Salcido's remarks.<ref name=\"Teacher Removed From City Council\"/> Salcido is forbidden from chairing or participating in any committees.\n\nA Pico Rivera eatery, Zapien's Salsa Grill, removed a popular lunch special named after Salcido after the  video surfaced. The lunch special, called \"The Mayor,\" was a common dish consisting of two enchiladas frequently ordered by Salcido, a regular at the restaurant. In a statement, the restaurant's proprietor said, \"I am outraged by what he said against our military personnel and our veterans.\"<ref name=\"Pico Rivera eatery takes \u2018The Mayor,\u2019 off the menu\">{{cite web\n|url = https://www.presstelegram.com/2018/01/29/amid-controversy-pico-rivera-eatery-takes-the-mayor-named-after-gregory-salcido-off-the-menu/\n|title = Pico Rivera eatery takes \u2018The Mayor,\u2019 off the menu \n|publisher = Press Telegram\n}}</ref><ref name=\"Zapien's Salsa Grill Lunch Specials\">{{cite web\n|url = http://thesalsagrill.com/menu/lunch-specials\n|title = Lunch Specials\n|publisher = Zapien's Salsa Grill\n}}</ref>\n\nOn Friday, February 1st, classes at El Rancho were cancelled as a protest took place across the street from the school. The event was covered by local media sources.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.whittierdailynews.com/2018/02/01/classes-canceled-for-el-rancho-high-students-friday-same-day-as-gregory-salcido-protest-planned/|title=Classes canceled for El Rancho High students Friday, same day as Gregory Salcido protest planned|date=2018-02-02|work=Whittier Daily News|access-date=2018-02-16|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nSalcido was finally fired by the El Rancho Unified School District on March 20, 2018. The event caused explosive cheering when the results of an investigation was announced to the general public at a school board meeting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/us/2018/03/21/teacher-who-called-military-lowest-low-is-fired.html\n|title=Teacher who called military 'lowest of the low' is fired|work=Fox News}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n<references />\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Salcido, Gregory}}\n[[Category:Mayors of places in California]]\n[[Category:People from Pico Rivera, California]]\n[[Category:Whittier College alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:California city council members]]\n[[Category:American schoolteachers]]\n[[Category:People from East Los Angeles, California]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:Candidates in the 2002 United States elections]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toProgressive(link changed toProgressivism) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gregory_Salcido"}
{"title_page": "1892 Legislative Session of the Hawaiian Kingdom", "text_new": "{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2018}}\n[[File:Ali\u02bbi\u014dlani Hale at midday.jpg|thumb|350px|The Legislative Assembly of 1892 met at the seat of government at [[Aliiolani Hale|Ali\u02bbi\u014dlani Hale]] (pictured) which was situated across the street from [[\u02bbIolani Palace]]]]\nThe '''1892 Session of the Legislature of the Hawaiian Kingdom''', also known as the '''Longest Legislature''', was a period from May 28, 1892, to January 14, 1893, in which the [[Legislature of the Hawaiian Kingdom|legislative assembly]] of the [[Hawaiian Kingdom]] met for its traditional bi-annual session. This [[unicameral]] body was composed of the upper House of Nobles and the lower House of Representatives. This would be the first session during the reign of Queen [[Liliuokalani|Lili\u02bbuokalani]] and the last meeting of the legislative assembly during the Hawaiian monarchy. Three days after the prorogation of the assembly, many of the political tension developed during the legislative debates and the queen's attempt to promulgate a new constitution while her legislators were not in session led to the [[overthrow of the Hawaiian Kingdom]] on January 17, 1893.\n\nMembers of this legislative session included citizens and subjects of the kingdom of either full or mixed [[Native Hawaiian]], Euro-American and Asian descent, who were divided across different party lines. They included the insurgents who would play an eventual role in the deposition of the queen, and also the political resistance leaders who would lead the [[Opposition to the overthrow of the Hawaiian Kingdom|opposition to the overthrow]] and attempts to annex the Hawaiian Islands to the United States.\n\n==Background==\n[[File:Bayonet Constitution political cartoon 1887.jpg|thumb|Political cartoon depicting the ''coup d'\u00e9tat'' which resulted in the signing of the Bayonet Constitution, 1887]]\nIn 1887, King [[Kal\u0101kaua]] was forced to sign the [[Bayonet Constitution]] under duress by the [[Hawaiian League]], a group of foreign businessman and Hawaiian subjects of American missionary descent including [[Lorrin A. Thurston]]. This constitution limited the absolute power of the monarch and strengthened the power of the executive cabinet. It also raised property requirements for suffrage, disenfranchised many poor Native Hawaiians and naturalized Asian citizens, and gave the vote to unnaturalized foreign residents of European or American descent. It also changed membership in the House of Nobles, the upper house of the legislature, from life appointments by the king to elected offices for the first time. A new cabinet headed by Thurston was imposed on the king and the king's previous administration headed by [[Walter Murray Gibson]] was ousted.{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|pages=344\u2013372}}\n\nThe instigators of this ''coup d'\u00e9tat'' formed the [[Reform Party (Hawaii)|Reform Party]], drawing its memberships from Hawaiian conservatives and citizens of foreign descent, and won the majority of the seats in the legislature in the election of 1887, which was mandated by the new constitution.{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|pages=406\u2013410}}{{sfn|Osorio|2002|pages=238, 245\u2013248}} In the election of 1890, the [[Hui K\u0101lai\u02bb\u0101ina]] (Hawaiian Political Association) and the Mechanics' and Workingmen's Political Protective Union joined together to form the [[National Reform Party (Hawaii)|National Reform Party]] in opposition to the Reform Party in this session. The Reform Party lost their majority control in the legislature and the Thurston cabinet was removed by a legislative vote of want of confidence.{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|pages=448\u2013455, 460\u2013460}}\n\nFollowing the [[wikt:prorogation#Noun|prorogation]] of the legislature of 1890, King Kalakaua died while in [[San Francisco]] and was succeeded by his sister Queen [[Liliuokalani|Lili\u02bbuokalani]] on January 29, 1891.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=474\u2013475}}</ref>\n\n==Election of 1892==\n\nThe general election of 1892 proved the most contentious. The four major parties were the Reform, National Reform, National Liberal, and the Native Sons of Hawaii which ran the same candidates as the National Reformers. The National Reform Party became the administration or governmental party and gained the personal support of the new queen. They joined with the Reformers and Native Sons in opposing the more radical elements of the National Liberal. The National Liberal Party, which became the party of the opposition, advocated for increased Native Hawaiian participation in the government and a constitutional convention to draft a new constitution to replace the unpopular Bayonet Constitution. However, the Liberals soon became divided between radicals and more conciliatory groups. [[Joseph N\u0101wah\u012b]] and [[William P\u016bnohu White]] became the leaders of the factions of the Liberals loyal to the queen against the more radical members led by [[John E. Bush (politician)|John E. Bush]] and [[Robert William Wilcox]], who were advocating for drastic changes such as increased power for the people and a republican form of government.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=514\u2013522, 547, 554\u2013555}}</ref>\n\nThe election resulted in a divided legislature, although the conservatives painted it as a victory for their coalition. It was hard to tell where the exact loyalty of many of the elected nobles and representatives lay because of internal disagreement. According to historian [[Ralph S. Kuykendall]], \"the party composition of the 1892 legislature (the forty-eight elected members) appeared to be: Reform Party, twenty-three; Liberal Party, thirteen; National Reform Party, nine; Independent, three\".{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|page=521}}\n\n==Legislative Session==\nFrom May 28, 1892, to January 14, 1893, the legislature of the Kingdom convened for an unprecedented 171 days, which later historians such as [[Albertine Loomis]] and [[Helena G. Allen]] dubbed the \"Longest Legislature\".<ref name=\"Longest\" /> This would be the first session during the reign of Queen Lili\u02bbuokalani and the last meeting of the legislative assembly during the Hawaiian monarchy.<ref name=\"Longest\">{{harvnb|Loomis|1963|pages=7\u201327}}; {{harvnb|Allen|1982|pages=269\u2013270}}</ref>\n\nAt the opening of the legislature, forty-eight elected politicians, consisting of twenty-four nobles (including thirteen holdovers continued their terms from the 1890 legislature) and twenty-four representatives from the four main Hawaiian Islands met at the legislative halls of [[Aliiolani Hale|Ali\u02bbi\u014dlani Hale]] in Honolulu. The legislature met as a [[unicameral]] body composed of the upper House of Nobles and the lower House of Representatives with Noble [[John Smith Walker]] presiding as President of the Legislative Assembly and Noble [[John Kauhane]] as Vice-President. The body included politicians of Native Hawaiian descent, Euro-American descent, mixed Hawaiian and Euro-American descent, and even three members of Chinese-Hawaiian descent. The appointed cabinet ministers also had the right to participate as ex-officio members of the legislature with the right to vote on all matters except on votes for their removal. In the course of the session, five members would resign and three new members chosen in special elections to replace with two of the five members reclaiming their vacated seats.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|page=521}}; {{harvnb|Hawaii|Lydecker|1918|page=182}}</ref>\n\nThis session was dominated by political infighting within and between and the different parties. Debates heard on the floor of the houses concerned the popular demand for a new constitution, the passage of a lottery bill and an opium licensing bill, aimed at alleviating the economic crisis caused by the [[McKinley Tariff]].<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=523\u2013581}}; {{harvnb|Loomis|1963|pages=7\u201327}}</ref> By the end of the session, the queen had also signed into law the lottery bill and opium licensing bill, which were extremely controversial in the foreign community and especially with the leaders of the Reform Party.{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|pages=543\u2013545, 574\u2013581}}\n\nPetitions asking for a new constitution were submitted by seven legislators: Noble [[David William Pua]] and Representatives [[Joseph N\u0101wah\u012b]], [[William P\u016bnohu White]], [[Jose Kekahuna Iosepa]], [[Anakalea Kauhi]], [[T. S. Nahinu]], [[Luther W. P. Kanealii]] and [[George Panila Kamauoha]].{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|pages=528\u2013529, 548}}{{sfn|Liliuokalani|1898|page=384}} Attempts were made to call a constitutional convention to draft a new constitution in both the 1890 session and the 1892 session. Both National Liberals and National Reformers campaigned on the promise of a new constitution, however many National Reformers supported a middle path and advocated for changes via amendments. The conservative Reformers would not tolerate any changes to the existing constitution. There was also disagreement on the legality of how to execute the change. No clear comparable precedents existed, since previous constitutions had been promulgated by the sovereign.{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|pages=461\u2013465, 547\u2013548, 575\u2013576}}\n\nThe main issue of contention between the new monarch and the legislators was the retention of her cabinet ministers; political division prevented Lili\u02bbuokalani from appointing a balanced council. The 1887 constitution retained the monarch's right to appoint her own cabinet minister but gave the legislature the power to vote for the dismissal of her cabinet.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=549\u2013559}}</ref> \nSeven resolutions of want of confidence were introduced during this session, and four of her self-appointed cabinets (the [[Hermann A. Widemann|Widemann]], [[Edward C. Macfarlane|Macfarlane]], [[William H. Cornwell|Cornwell]], and  [[George Norton Wilcox|Wilcox]] cabinets) were ousted by votes of the legislature.<ref>{{harvnb|Moblo|1998|pages=229\u2013232}}</ref>\n\nOn January 13, 1893, after the legislature dismissed the Wilcox cabinet (which had political sympathies to the Reform Party), Lili\u02bbuokalani appointed the new Parker cabinet, which had ties to the National Reform Party and consisted of [[Samuel Parker (Hawaii)|Samuel Parker]], as minister of foreign affairs; [[John F. Colburn]], as minister of the interior; [[William H. Cornwell]], as minister of finance; and [[Arthur P. Peterson]], as attorney general.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=562\u2013563, 573\u2013581}}; {{harvnb|Allen|1982|page=174\u2013175}}; {{harvnb|Moblo|1998|pages=229\u2013232}}</ref><ref name=\"Ministers\"/>\n\n[[File:Liliuokalani leaving Aliiolani Hale in 1893.jpg|thumb|Queen Lili\u02bbuokalani leaving Aliiolani Hale following the prorogation ceremony, 1893]]\n\nThe legislative assembly was prorogued January 14, at a noon ceremony officiated by the queen at Ali\u02bbi\u014dlani Hale, which was situated across the street from [[\u02bbIolani Palace]].<ref name=\"Prorogation\">{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=579}}; {{harvnb|Alexander|1896|pages=30\u201331}}; {{cite news|title=The Legislature|newspaper=The Daily Bulletin|location=Honolulu|date=January 14, 1893|page=3|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016412/1893-01-14/ed-1/seq-3/|access-date=December 25, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226130301/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn82016412/1893-01-14/ed-1/seq-3/|archive-date=December 26, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n== Aftermath ==\nFollowing the prorogation of the legislative session, Lili\u02bbuokalani attempted to promulgate a [[1893 Constitution of the Hawaiian Kingdom|new constitution]] while the legislature was not in session. In reaction to the legislative stand still on the constitution convention bill, the queen met in secret with the two leaders of the Liberal Party: Representatives N\u0101wah\u012b and White and [[Samuel Nowlein]], the captain of her Royal Guards, to draft a new constitution.{{sfn|Kuykendall|1967|pages=582\u2013586}}\n\nIn the afternoon of January 14, she met with her cabinet ministers while members of Hui K\u0101lai\u02bb\u0101ina and a delegation of native legislators marched to \u02bbIolani Palace with a sealed package containing the constitution for her to promulgate. According to historian [[William DeWitt Alexander]], this was pre-planned by the queen.<ref name=\"Kuykendall 1967 pages=582\u2013586\">{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=582\u2013586}}; {{harvnb|Allen|1982|pages=281\u2013282}}; {{harvnb|Twigg-Smith|1998|pages=64\u201367}}; {{harvnb|Alexander|1896|pages=29\u201336}}</ref> However, she discovered the ministers were either opposed to or reluctant to sign the new constitution and the queen had to postpone her plans and dismiss the delegations of political leaders and the assembled crowds from the palace.<ref name=\"Kuykendall 1967 pages=582\u2013586\"/> She later wrote, \"I told them I would not have taken such a step if they had not encouraged me. They had led me out to the edge of a precipice, and now were leaving me to take the step alone.\"{{sfn|Liliuokalani|1898|page=385}}\n\nThe political fallout of the queen's actions led to citywide political rallies and meetings in Honolulu. Anti-monarchists, annexationists, and leading Reformist politicians, including legislators Lorrin A. Thurston, [[William Owen Smith]], and William Chauncey Wilder, formed the [[Committee of Safety (Hawaii)|Committee of Safety]] in protest of the \"revolutionary\" action of the queen and conspired to depose her. In response, royalists and loyalists formed the Committee of Law and Order and met at the palace square on January{{nbsp}}16. White, N\u0101wah\u012b, Bush, Wilcox, and [[Antone Rosa]] and other pro-monarchist leaders gave speeches in support for the queen and the government.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=586\u2013594}}; {{harvnb|Alexander|1896|pages=37\u201351}}; {{harvnb|Twigg-Smith|1998|pages=135\u2013166}}</ref> These actions and the radicalized political climate eventually led to the [[Overthrow of the Hawaiian Kingdom|overthrow of the monarchy]], on January{{nbsp}}17, 1893, by the Committee of Safety, with the covert support of United States Minister [[John L. Stevens]] and the landing of American forces from the [[USS Boston (1884)|USS ''Boston'']]. After a brief transition under the [[Provisional Government of Hawaii|Provisional Government]], the oligarchical [[Republic of Hawaii]] was established on July{{nbsp}}4, 1894, with [[Sanford B. Dole]] as president.<ref>{{harvnb|Kuykendall|1967|pages=586\u2013605, 649}}; {{harvnb|Loomis|1963|pages=25\u201326}}</ref>{{sfn|Silva|2004|pages=129\u2013163}} During this period, the de{{nbsp}}facto government was composed largely of residents of American and European ancestry, although a few Native Hawaiians from the 1892 legislature: John Ena, John Kauhane, and Jose Kekahuna Iosepa signed the constitutional convention for the Republic while Kauhane and George Panila Kamauoha would serve multiple terms in the legislature of the Republic.<ref>{{harvnb|Blount|1895|page=1371}}; {{harvnb|Hawaii|Lydecker|1918|pages=225\u2013226, 231, 236, 239, 247}}</ref>\n\nMany of the former legislators of the 1892 session, including Robert William Wilcox and Joseph N\u0101wah\u012b, would lead the [[Opposition to the overthrow of the Hawaiian Kingdom|opposition to the overthrow]] and resistance to annexation of the Hawaiian Islands to the United States. In 1893, Nawahi and many former 1892 legislators founded the [[Hui Aloha \u02bb\u0100ina]] (Hawaiian Patriotic League), a patriotic group founded to protest annexation, while Wilcox led an unsuccessful [[1895 Counter-revolution of Hawaii|counter-revolution]] in 1895 to restore the monarchy.<ref>{{harvnb|Silva|2004|page=138}}; {{harvnb|Blount|1895|pages=1294\u20131298}}; {{cite news|title=Patriotic Leaguers \u2013 They Determine On Secret Actions \u2013 A Demand for the Restoration of the Monarchy Favored|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=May 2, 1893|page=5|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1893-05-02/ed-1/seq-5/|access-date=February 8, 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171226073905/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1893-05-02/ed-1/seq-5/|archive-date=December 26, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Members of the Legislative Assembly==\n===House of Nobles===\nThis incomplete breakdown of party allegiance are based on ''The Pacific Commercial Advertiser'', a contemporary newspaper, reporting at the beginning of the legislative session and the report of Noble Edward C. MacFarlane in the [[Blount Report]].<ref name=\"Election\" /><ref name=\"Blount\" />\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"border-style:solid;border-width:1px;border-color:#808080\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"2\" \n|-\n! Name !! District !! Party at Election !! Party (Blount Report) !!style=\"width:40%;\"| Notes !!class=\"unsortable\"| Sources\n|-\n|{{sortname|Robert Renton|Hind}}\n|[[Hawaii (island)|Hawaii]]\n|Reform\n|Independent\n|\n|<ref name=\"Lydecker\">{{harvnb|Hawaii|Lydecker|1918|page=182}}</ref><ref name=\"Election\">{{cite news|title=List Of Candidates|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=February 3, 1892|page=4|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1892-02-03/ed-1/seq-4/|access-date=December 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171125080827/https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1892-02-03/ed-1/seq-4/|archive-date=November 25, 2017|url-status=live|df=mdy-all}}; {{cite news|title=Legislature Of 1892|newspaper=The Pacific Commercial Advertiser|location=Honolulu|date=February 26, 1892|page=1|url=http://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn85047084/1892-02-26/ed-1/seq-1/|access-date=Decembe